{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523089"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:52:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:52:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13872"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13872"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.18,0.21,0.4,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6489"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52724"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6489"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13872"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38092"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1164"},{"type":"tags","id":"5864"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12882"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12883"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45685"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52724"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of left-sided facial weakness. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals a partial left-sided facial weakness involving the lower face but sparing the forehead (Image). During the examination, she experiences a focal seizure involving her left arm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely anatomical location of the lesion causing this clinical picture?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Right facial nerve","Left facial nucleus","Right internal capsule","Right cerebral cortex","Left pons"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms consistent with an upper motor neuron lesion affecting the left side of her face, likely due to a lesion in the \u003Cstrong\u003Eright cerebral cortex\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient\u0027s symptoms of left-sided facial weakness (sparing the forehead) and focal seizures of the left arm are consistent with a lesion in the right cerebral cortex. Additionally, the sparing of her forehead muscles is a key feature in differentiating upper motor neuron from lower motor neuron facial nerve palsy. Lesions in the cerebral cortex typically cause contralateral symptoms due to the crossing of motor pathways in the brainstem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eright facial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because a lesion here would cause a lower motor neuron facial palsy, affecting all facial muscles on the right side, including the forehead. It would not explain the left-sided symptoms or seizures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft facial nucleus\u003C/strong\u003E, located in the brainstem, would cause a lower motor neuron facial palsy if affected, involving all facial muscles on the left side, including the forehead. It would not account for the seizures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA lesion in the \u003Cstrong\u003Eright internal capsule\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially cause left-sided facial weakness, but it would typically be accompanied by more prominent arm and leg weakness (hemiparesis). It would also be unusual for a capsular lesion to cause focal seizures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile a lesion in the \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft pons\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially cause left-sided facial weakness, it would typically present with additional ipsilateral cranial nerve deficits and contralateral limb weakness (crossed findings). It would not explain the focal seizures in the left arm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case highlights the importance of localizing neurological lesions based on the pattern of symptoms. The presentation of contralateral facial weakness sparing the forehead, along with focal seizures, strongly points to a cortical lesion. The absence of prominent limb weakness or other brainstem signs makes a cortical lesion the most likely explanation for this patient\u0027s symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Upper motor neuron facial nerve palsy typically spares the forehead muscles due to bilateral innervation.","Space-occupying lesions in the cerebral cortex can cause contralateral facial weakness and seizures.","Careful neurological examination and history-taking are crucial in localizing lesions in the absence of imaging."],"references":["Wallwork B, Panizza B, Phan NT. A general practice approach to Bell\u2019s palsy. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2016;45:794-7. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2016/november/a-general-practice-approach-to-bell-s-palsy","Induruwa I, Holland N, Gregory R, Khadjooi K. The impact of misdiagnosing Bell\u0027s palsy as acute stroke. Clin Med (Lond). 2019 Nov;19(6):494-498. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6899254/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38092"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13872"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20814"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20814"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/WwzNMEa6ffss0bbkDb5vcAE5IC8Qkt.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/WwzNMEa6ffss0bbkDb5vcAE5IC8Qkt.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38092"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-09T12:30:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-09T12:32:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6489"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52724"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"headi